{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> |title = Lowlife |image = Tall-lowlife.jpg |imagesize = <!-- default 250 --> |caption = {{Descript-cvr|A Complete Lowlife|||1997}} For the [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]] collected edition. Art by [[Ed Brubaker]]. |schedule = |format = |limited = Y |Crime = y |publisher = [[Caliber Comics]], [[MU Press]] |date = 1992–1995 |issues = 5 |main_char_team = |writers = [[Ed Brubaker]] |artists = [[Ed Brubaker]] |pencillers = |inkers = |letterers = |colorists = |editors = |creative_team_month = |creative_team_year = |creators = |TPB = A Complete Lowlife |ISBN = 0-9698874-7-7 |subcat = |sort = Lowlife (comics) |addpubcat1 = Caliber Comics titles |nonUS = }} '''''Lowlife''''' is a semi-autobiographical [[comic book]] series written and drawn by [[Ed Brubaker]], originally published by [[Caliber Comics]] and later [[Aeon Press]]. Collected editions were put out by Aeon and [[Black Eye Books]].
The ''Comics Journal'' described the book as following the "frustration and cynicism of disenchanted [[slacker]] kids finding excitement in their uneventful lives."<ref>[http://www.tcj.com/2_archives/r_Pr2Sm.html "''Like Teen President'' to ''Smell of Steve''"], ''[[The Comics Journal]]'' #79</ref> The series was described by ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'' as "part fiction, part autobiography, the narratives hover between sincerity and parody, with moments of transcendence that lift it out of the realm of the ordinary comic book."{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}
Brubaker cited his work here as an influence on later works: {{cquote|I'm exploring the same themes in my ''[[Batman]]'' comics and my ''[[Catwoman (comic book)|Catwoman]]'' comics that I was probably exploring in ''Lowlife'': family relationships, personal relationships, people not being able to escape their past. . . . That's the stuff that interests me, and that's the stuff I write about.<ref name=newsarama />}}
==Development and publication history== ''Lowlife'' was Brubaker's first professional work.<ref name=newsarama>[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=144764 "Behind the Page: Ed Brubaker I"]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Newsarama]], January 28, 2008.</ref> The work is semi-autobiographical, based upon the lives of the author and his friends but "with the names changed."<ref name=newsarama />
''Lowlife'' debuted in 1992 with two issues published by [[Caliber Comics]]. Issues #3–5 were published in 1994–1995 by the [[MU Press]] imprint [[Aeon Press]].
==Collected editions== The series has been collected into a number of [[trade paperback (comics)|trade paperbacks]]: *''The Portable Lowlife'' (48 pages, [[Aeon]], 1995, {{ISBN|1-883847-16-8}}) *''A Complete Lowlife'' (112 pages, Black Eye Books, 1997, {{ISBN|0-9698874-7-7}}, [[Top Shelf Productions]], 2001, {{ISBN|1-891830-20-1}})
